<div id="main_content">
	<h2>UCF Latin American Studies Program Reinvigorated Under New Director</h2>
	
	<p class="article_info">
		
			By Sae Schatz
		
		<span class="date">Sept. 14, 2004</span></p>
	
	
	
	
	
	
	
	
	
		
			<div id="related">
				<h3>Related Contacts and Links:</h3>
				<ul>
		
		<li>
		
			
				<h4><a href="mailto:martfern@mail.ucf.edu">Luis Martínez-Fernández</a></h4>
			
			
			
				<ul>
				<li>407-823-1174</li>
			
			</ul>
		
		</li>
	
	
	
		
		<li>
		
			<h4><a href="http://www.cas.ucf.edu/LACLS/ ">Latin American, Caribbean and Latino Studies</a></h4>
		
		</li>
	
	
	 </ul></div> 
	
	
			
	
	
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	<div id="share">
		<ul><li><p id="print"><a href="javascript:window.print();">Print this Page</a></li></ul>
	
	</div>
	
	
	
	
		
			<p class="MsoNormal" style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt"><font face="Arial"><span style="FONT-SIZE: 12pt">The UCF Latin American, </span><place /><span style="FONT-SIZE: 12pt">Caribbean</span></place /><span style="FONT-SIZE: 12pt"> and Latino Studies program received a new name, a new director and new initiatives this year. </span></font></p><p class="MsoNormal" style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt"><font face="Arial"><span style="FONT-SIZE: 12pt"> </span></font></p><p class="MsoNormal" style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt"><font face="Arial"><span style="FONT-SIZE: 12pt"></span></font><font face="Arial"><span style="FONT-SIZE: 12pt">Formerly called Latin American and Iberian Studies, the program now reflects a broader focus that includes courses and scholarly activities on the Hispanic population in the </span><country-region /><place /><span style="FONT-SIZE: 12pt">United States</span></place /></country-region /><span style="FONT-SIZE: 12pt">.</span></font></p><p class="MsoNormal" style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt"><font face="Arial"><span style="FONT-SIZE: 12pt"> </span></font></p><p class="MsoNormal" style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt"><font face="Arial"><span style="FONT-SIZE: 12pt"></span></font><a name="OLE_LINK1"><span style="FONT-SIZE: 12pt"><font face="Arial">Luis Martínez-Fernández, a scholar of the histories of </font></span></a><font face="Arial"><country-region /><place /><span style="mso-bookmark: OLE_LINK1"><span style="FONT-SIZE: 12pt">Cuba</span></span></place /></country-region /><span style="mso-bookmark: OLE_LINK1"><span style="FONT-SIZE: 12pt">, </span></span><place /><span style="mso-bookmark: OLE_LINK1"><span style="FONT-SIZE: 12pt">Puerto Rico</span></span></place /><span style="mso-bookmark: OLE_LINK1"><span style="FONT-SIZE: 12pt"> and the </span></span><country-region /><place /><span style="mso-bookmark: OLE_LINK1"><span style="FONT-SIZE: 12pt">Dominican Republic</span></span></place /></country-region /><span style="mso-bookmark: OLE_LINK1"><span style="FONT-SIZE: 12pt">, is directing the program. He came to UCF this fall from </span></span><place /><placename /><span style="mso-bookmark: OLE_LINK1"><span style="FONT-SIZE: 12pt">Rutgers</span></span></placename /><span style="mso-bookmark: OLE_LINK1"><span style="FONT-SIZE: 12pt"> </span></span><placetype /><span style="mso-bookmark: OLE_LINK1"><span style="FONT-SIZE: 12pt">University</span></span></placetype /></place /><span style="mso-bookmark: OLE_LINK1"><span style="FONT-SIZE: 12pt">, where he chaired the Puerto Rican and Hispanic Caribbean Studies Department. Martínez-Fernández holds a doctoral degree from </span></span><place /><placename /><span style="mso-bookmark: OLE_LINK1"><span style="FONT-SIZE: 12pt">Duke</span></span></placename /><span style="mso-bookmark: OLE_LINK1"><span style="FONT-SIZE: 12pt"> </span></span><placetype /><span style="mso-bookmark: OLE_LINK1"><span style="FONT-SIZE: 12pt">University</span></span></placetype /></place /><span style="mso-bookmark: OLE_LINK1"><span style="FONT-SIZE: 12pt"> and has written extensively on the </span></span><place /><span style="mso-bookmark: OLE_LINK1"><span style="FONT-SIZE: 12pt">Caribbean</span></span></place /><span style="mso-bookmark: OLE_LINK1"><span style="FONT-SIZE: 12pt">. His most acclaimed book is Fighting Slavery in the </span></span><place /><span style="mso-bookmark: OLE_LINK1"><span style="FONT-SIZE: 12pt">Caribbean</span></span></place /><span style="mso-bookmark: OLE_LINK1"><span style="FONT-SIZE: 12pt">, and his most recent work is the two-volume Encyclopedia of Cuba. </span></span></font></p><p class="MsoNormal" style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt"><font face="Arial"><span style="mso-bookmark: OLE_LINK1"><span style="FONT-SIZE: 12pt"> </span></span></font></p><p class="MsoNormal" style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt"><font face="Arial"><span style="mso-bookmark: OLE_LINK1"><span style="FONT-SIZE: 12pt"></span></span></font><font face="Arial"><span style="FONT-SIZE: 12pt">Martínez-Fernández plans to expand the Latin American studies programs influence at UCF, the </span><place /><span style="FONT-SIZE: 12pt">Central Florida</span></place /><span style="FONT-SIZE: 12pt"> community and nationally, and he wants to foster and support new research locally.</span></font></p><p class="MsoNormal" style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt"><font face="Arial"><span style="FONT-SIZE: 12pt"> </span></font></p><p class="MsoNormal" style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt"><font face="Arial"><span style="FONT-SIZE: 12pt"></span></font><span style="FONT-SIZE: 12pt"><font face="Arial">It is very important to me, personally, to make sure the program establishes a presence and influence within the university -- not something at the margins, but at the very epicenter, he said. </font></span></p><p class="MsoNormal" style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt"><span style="FONT-SIZE: 12pt"> </span></p><p class="MsoNormal" style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt"><span style="FONT-SIZE: 12pt"></span><font face="Arial"><span style="FONT-SIZE: 12pt">The Latin American, </span><place /><span style="FONT-SIZE: 12pt">Caribbean</span></place /><span style="FONT-SIZE: 12pt"> and Latino Studies program offers classes in art, languages, history, anthropology and politics. The courses give students a working knowledge of Latin American, </span><place /><span style="FONT-SIZE: 12pt">Caribbean</span></place /><span style="FONT-SIZE: 12pt"> and U.S. Hispanic populations. The program offers an 18-credit hour minor and, with the approval of the Board of Trustees, could be expanded to offer bachelor's degrees.</span></font></p><p class="MsoNormal" style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt"><font face="Arial"><span style="FONT-SIZE: 12pt"> </span></font></p><p class="MsoNormal" style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt"><font face="Arial"><span style="FONT-SIZE: 12pt"></span></font><font face="Arial"><span style="FONT-SIZE: 12pt">The knowledge students gain from the program can be applied to many careers, including social and community services, education, public relations, journalism, foreign service and international commerce.</span></font></p><p class="MsoNormal" style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt"><font face="Arial"><span style="FONT-SIZE: 12pt"> </span></font></p><p class="MsoNormal" style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt"><font face="Arial"><span style="FONT-SIZE: 12pt"></span></font><span style="FONT-SIZE: 12pt"><font face="Arial">One of Martínez-Fernándezs first efforts will be the establishment of an advisory board. The programs faculty want to ensure that the boards membership is diverse. The board will include local business leaders, community leaders and educators, along with UCF students, alumni and faculty. The advisory board will collaborate with local groups, such as policy makers, businesses, schools and the media. </font></span></p><p class="MsoNormal" style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt"><span style="FONT-SIZE: 12pt"> </span></p><p class="MsoNormal" style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt"><span style="FONT-SIZE: 12pt"></span><span style="FONT-SIZE: 12pt"><font face="Arial">Understanding Latin Americans and Latinos is essential not only for students and faculty members, Martínez-Fernández said. This knowledge is critical for policy makers, businesses, employers, as well as for people like my UCF colleagues and me who are interested in the scholarly dimension of such studies.</font></span></p><p class="MsoNormal" style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt"><span style="FONT-SIZE: 12pt"> </span></p><p class="MsoNormal" style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt"><span style="FONT-SIZE: 12pt"></span><font face="Arial"><span style="FONT-SIZE: 12pt">Martínez-Fernández called </span><place /><span style="FONT-SIZE: 12pt">Central Florida</span></place /><span style="FONT-SIZE: 12pt"> a magnet for immigrants from </span><place /><span style="FONT-SIZE: 12pt">Latin America</span></place /><span style="FONT-SIZE: 12pt"> and the </span><place /><span style="FONT-SIZE: 12pt">Caribbean</span></place /><span style="FONT-SIZE: 12pt">. He said the region offers many possibilities for innovative research on the numerous exchanges between the </span><country-region /><place /><span style="FONT-SIZE: 12pt">United States</span></place /></country-region /><span style="FONT-SIZE: 12pt">, </span><place /><span style="FONT-SIZE: 12pt">Latin America</span></place /><span style="FONT-SIZE: 12pt">, and the </span><place /><span style="FONT-SIZE: 12pt">Caribbean</span></place /><span style="FONT-SIZE: 12pt">, as well as the interactions among the various Latino groups living in </span><state /><place /><span style="FONT-SIZE: 12pt">Florida</span></place /></state /><span style="FONT-SIZE: 12pt">. </span></font></p><p class="MsoNormal" style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt"><font face="Arial"><span style="FONT-SIZE: 12pt"> </span></font></p><p class="MsoNormal" style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt"><font face="Arial"><span style="FONT-SIZE: 12pt"></span></font><font face="Arial"><span style="FONT-SIZE: 12pt">UCF decided to focus more attention on the study of Hispanics in the </span><country-region /><place /><span style="FONT-SIZE: 12pt">United States</span></place /></country-region /><span style="FONT-SIZE: 12pt"> largely because </span><place /><span style="FONT-SIZE: 12pt">Latin America</span></place /><span style="FONT-SIZE: 12pt"> and the </span><country-region /><place /><span style="FONT-SIZE: 12pt">United States</span></place /></country-region /><span style="FONT-SIZE: 12pt">, particularly states such as </span><state /><place /><span style="FONT-SIZE: 12pt">Florida</span></place /></state /><span style="FONT-SIZE: 12pt">, influence one anothers cultures, economies, and politics. Martínez-Fernández said the architecture in </span><city /><place /><span style="FONT-SIZE: 12pt">Miami</span></place /></city /><span style="FONT-SIZE: 12pt">, the changing diet patters in the </span><country-region /><place /><span style="FONT-SIZE: 12pt">United States</span></place /></country-region /><span style="FONT-SIZE: 12pt"> and money that some </span><country-region /><place /><span style="FONT-SIZE: 12pt">U.S.</span></place /></country-region /><span style="FONT-SIZE: 12pt"> immigrants send to their families in </span><place /><span style="FONT-SIZE: 12pt">Latin America</span></place /><span style="FONT-SIZE: 12pt"> are examples of how the cultures are connected.</span></font></p><p class="MsoNormal" style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt"><font face="Arial"><span style="FONT-SIZE: 12pt"> </span></font></p><p class="MsoNormal" style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt"><font face="Arial"><span style="FONT-SIZE: 12pt"></span></font><span style="FONT-SIZE: 12pt"><font face="Arial">For more information on the program go to </font><a href="http://www.cas.ucf.edu/LACLS"><font face="Arial">www.cas.ucf.edu/LACLS</font></a><font face="Arial"> or call Martínez-Fernández at 407-823-1174 or Mercedes Hutchinson, program assistant, at 407-823-1173.</font></span></p><p class="MsoNormal" style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt"><span style="FONT-SIZE: 12pt"><font face="Arial"> </font></span></p>
		
	
	<p id="back"><a href="index?page=news">&lt; Back to the Newsroom</a></p>

